An affinity diagramming is a process or method by which many ideas or pieces of data are created and/or organized into categories or groups by a team of people. It is typically used for generating ideas to solve a particular problem.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid6775699 \tab The process requires 
a team of people, preferably of four to six people who are each very experienced and knowledgeable in different areas. The team must first have a goal to reach or problem to solve and discuss the situation thoroughly so as to make sure everyone has a clea
r
 view of what needs to be done. Then there is a brainstorming or idea-generation period in which various ideas are discussed. During this period, everyone writes down ideas on post-it notes. Every idea goes on a separate note, and the notes must clearly e
x
press a whole concept (not just a single word for example). After a while, the post-it notes are posted on the wall in random places. Then there is a sorting phase, in which everyone moves the notes toward other cards that have ideas that may go together 
somehow, and organize them into groups. No one talks during this period, so as not to interfere with how other people move things. After a while of this, groups and subgroups become well defined. }{\insrsid4330533 When groups can clearly be seen}{
\insrsid6775699 , header and subheader cards are created to give a concise title to the different groups and subgroups. After all of this, lines are drawn between heade}{\insrsid4330533 rs to form the affinity diagram.}{\insrsid6775699  }{\insrsid4330533 
The end result }{\insrsid6775699 is a typical diagram of organization.
