\par }{\b\insrsid6775699 Cognitive Maps}{\insrsid6775699 
\par \tab Cognitive maps are basically internal}{\insrsid4330533  (in the mind)}{\insrsid6775699  representations or models of outside things. These \'93maps\'94 are usually built up from experience, but they can a}{\insrsid4330533 
lso be imparted by other humans.}{\insrsid6775699 
\par \tab For example, after walking the same route every day, you get to know the route pretty well, including relative distances, landmarks, etc. This \'93knowing\'94
 is the cognitive map. After walking this route so many times, an internal representation of the route is built up and is pretty accurate.}{\insrsid4330533  Based on landmarks, one can judge where they are on thei
r internal map, and thus where they are in physical space.}{\insrsid6775699 
\par \tab The ability to read maps (cartographic maps) is really the ability translate an abstract representation of physical space (the map you are reading) to an internal map (cognitive map) of physical space, which can then be directly co}{\insrsid4659690 
mpared to actual physical space.}{\insrsid6775699 
\par \tab Cognitive maps are not limited to the special realm, they are used in all kinds of human activities. One kind of cognitive map }{\insrsid4659690 could be a}{\insrsid6775699  mental representation of how ideas and concepts are interrelated}{
\insrsid11283313 , a map of knowledge}{\insrsid6775699 . A pictorial representation of these kinds of cognitive maps or any set of interrelated concepts is termed a concept map.}{\insrsid11283313 
