\par }{\b\insrsid6775699 Cultural Probes}{\insrsid6775699 
\par \tab Cultural probes are used to do ethnographic studies in a relatively non-invasi
ve way. Traditionally, these kinds of studies are done by following someone of a group of people around and recording everything they do. This is pretty invasive, and does not work well with some kinds of people. The goal of cultural probes is to accompli
sh the same thing by providing the person(s) being studied means of self-documenting, then collecting that documentation after a period of time.}{\insrsid11283313 
 For example, a cultural probe package may contain a camera, a notebook, a voice recorder, and other things that could be used to self-document.}{\insrsid6775699 
 This has several main advantages; it makes the process less invasive, and it provides information about what the person being studied is thinking and feeling instead of only factual information.
\par \tab Cultural probing can be appl
ied in the design process as a means to learn more about the people and environment at which your design is targeted. For example, in designing a computer support system to assist people who are disabled, elderly, or former }{\insrsid11283313 psychiatric}
{\insrsid6775699  patients, conventional methods of ethnography such as direct observation of people is very invasi}{\insrsid11283313 ve, and sometimes inappropriate.}{\insrsid6775699  }{\insrsid11283313 C}{\insrsid6775699 ultural probes were used instead
}{\insrsid11283313 . (5)}{\insrsid6775699 
\par }{\insrsid11283313 \tab }{\insrsid8996895 The idea of cu}{\insrsid11283313 ltural probing }{\insrsid8996895 can be used to not only learn about a person\rquote 
s environment, but to let the probee make suggestions about what you are designing. This effectively distributes the design process, which may be very useful to any designer.}{\insrsid11283313 
