\par }{\b\insrsid6775699 Behavior Sampling}{\insrsid6775699 
\par \tab Behavior sampling is when behavior of a sample population is studied by means of observing the behavior of many single individuals. This is a common method in all behavioral studies, such as studies of animals, psychology, and neuroscience.
\par \tab Behavioral sampling is broken down into two methods: 1.) Focal-Animal sampl
ing - individuals are monitored continuously for a period of time. 2.) Spot Sampling - sample the behavior of individuals at random times throughout the study. Spot sampling is used often in anthropological studies, and is the basis for most time allocati
on research (researching how much time is spent on a given task on the average). Focal-animal sampling is commonly used in animal behavioral studies.
\par \tab These kinds of methods can be used in the design process to see how your target population will likely respond to your design, or to study how they are behaving with relation to pre-existing designs related to your target.
